If you're not seeing any logs, it could be because your server isn't encountering any errors or because your logging level is set to only show certain types of messages.

Here are a few things you can try:

1. **Add more logging statements.** You can add `console.log` statements in your server-side code to log more information. For example, you could log the request method and URL at the start of your handler function, and log the response status and body before sending the response.

```typescript
export default async function handler(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  console.log(`Received ${req.method} request for ${req.url}`);

  // ... rest of your code ...

  console.log(`Sending response with status ${res.statusCode}`);
  console.log(sizes, neighborhoods, cities);
  res.status(200).json({ sizes, neighborhoods, cities });
}
```

2. **Check your logging level.** If you're using a logging library or a server framework that includes logging, it might have a logging level setting that controls which types of messages are logged. Check the documentation for your logging library or server framework to see if this is the case.

3. **Check for silent failures.** Sometimes, an operation might fail without throwing an error or logging a message. This is often the case with network requests or database operations. If you suspect this might be happening, you can add error handling code to log an error message and respond with an error status.

```typescript
try {
  // ... your code ...
} catch (error) {
  console.error(`Error handling request: ${error.message}`);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
}
```

Remember, `console.log` statements in your server-side code will log to the server console, not the browser console. Make sure you're looking in the right place for your logs.

