The hydration error might be caused by the `Popover` component from `@typeform/embed-react`. This component might be trying to access browser-specific APIs during server-side rendering, which would cause an error.

To fix this, you can use dynamic imports to only load the `Popover` component on the client side. This way, the component will not be included in the server-side rendered HTML, and there will be no hydration error.

Here's how you can do this:

```typescriptreact
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

const TypeformSubmission = () => {
  const [Popover, setPopover] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    import('@typeform/embed-react')
      .then((module) => setPopover(() => module.Popover))
      .catch((error) => console.error('Failed to load @typeform/embed-react', error));
  }, []);

  if (!Popover) {
    return null; // or a loading spinner, or some fallback component
  }

  return (
    <div id='typeform' className="">
      <Popover 
        id="UR7SpT93" 
        buttonProps={{
          ariaLabel: 'Typeform Button',
        }}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default TypeformSubmission;
```

In this code, the `Popover` component is loaded dynamically in a `useEffect` hook. The `useEffect` hook is only run on the client side, so the `Popover` component will not be loaded during server-side rendering. If the `Popover` component is not loaded yet, the `TypeformSubmission` component returns `null`.

If you want to render the `Popover` component from `@typeform/embed-react` after everything else has mounted, you can use the `useEffect` hook with an empty dependency array. This will ensure that the effect runs only once, after the initial render.

Here's how you can do this:

```typescriptreact
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { Popover } from '@typeform/embed-react';

const TypeformSubmission = () => {
  const [isMounted, setIsMounted] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    setIsMounted(true);
  }, []);

  if (!isMounted) {
    return null; // or a loading spinner, or some fallback component
  }

  return (
    <div id='typeform' className="">
      <Popover 
        id="UR7SpT93" 
        buttonProps={{
          ariaLabel: 'Typeform Button',
        }}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default TypeformSubmission;
```

In this code, the `isMounted` state is initially `false`, so the `TypeformSubmission` component returns `null`. After the initial render, the `useEffect` hook runs and sets `isMounted` to `true`, causing a re-render. On the second render, the `Popover` component is returned.

